      "\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.3 -/\n\ndef parts₃ {α : Type} : List α → List (Partition α) :=\n  let step (x : α) : List (Partition α) → List (Partition α)\n   | [[]] => [[[x]]]\n   | ps => ps.map (cons x) ++ ps.map (glue x)\n  List.foldr step [[]]\n\n-- #eval parts₃ [1,2,3]\n\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.4 -/\n\nsection\nopen List (filter all head!)\n\ndef ok (xs : List Nat) : Bool :=  xs.all (· > 0)\n\ndef okextendl (x : Nat) : Partition Nat → List (Partition Nat) :=\n filter (ok ∘ head!) ∘ extendl x\n\nvariable (h : ∀ x ps, filter (flip all ok) (concatMap (extendl x) ps) =\n              concatMap (okextendl x) (filter (flip all ok) ps))\n\nexample\n  : List.filter (flip List.all ok) ∘ parts₁ = List.foldr (concatMap ∘ okextendl) [[]] := by\n  funext xs\n  unfold parts₁\n  simp [Function.comp]\n  induction xs with\n  | nil =>\n    simp [List.foldr, flip]\n  | cons a as ih =>\n    have h1 := h a\n    sorry\n\nend\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.5 -/\n\nsection\nopen List (range head! tail zipWith and)\n\ndef leftmin  (xs : List Nat) := xs.all (head! xs ≤ ·)\ndef rightmax (xs : List Nat) := xs.all (· ≤ last xs)\ndef ordered  (xs : List Nat) := and $ zipWith (· ≤ ·) xs (tail xs)\ndef nmatch   (xs : List Nat) := and $ zipWith (· ≠ ·) xs (range xs.length)\n\ndef suffixClosed (p : List Nat → Bool) : Prop :=\n    ∀ xs ys, p (xs ++ ys) → p ys\n\ndef prefixClosed (p : List Nat → Bool) : Prop :=\n    ∀ xs ys, p (xs ++ ys) → p xs\n\nexample : suffixClosed leftmin := by\n   unfold suffixClosed\n   intro xs ys\n   unfold leftmin; simp\n   intro h\n   sorry\n```\n\nWe need to complete the proof for `example : suffixClosed leftmin := by ...`.\n\nThe goal is to show that for any lists `xs` and `ys`, if `leftmin (xs ++ ys)` holds, then `leftmin ys` holds.\n\n`leftmin L` means `∀ x ∈ L, head! L ≤ x`.\n\nSo, the hypothesis `h` is `∀ x ∈ xs ++ ys, head! (xs ++ ys) ≤ x`.\nThe goal is `∀ x ∈ ys, head! ys ≤ x`.\n\nTo prove this, we need to show that if `x` is in `ys`, then `head! ys ≤ x`.\nWe know that `x` is in `ys`, so `x` is also in `xs ++ ys` (if `xs` is non-empty). From `h`, we have `head! (xs ++ ys) ≤ x`.\nWe need to relate `head! (xs ++ ys)` to `head! ys` and `head! xs`.\n\nCase analysis:\n1. If `xs` is non-empty: `head! (xs ++ ys) = head! xs`. From `h`, we get `head! xs ≤ x` for all `x` in `xs ++ ys`. In particular, for `x = head! ys` (if `ys` is non-empty), we get `head! xs ≤ head! ys`. For any `x` in `ys`, we have `head! xs ≤ x`. Since `head! ys ≤ head! xs`, we get `head! ys ≤ x` by transitivity.\n2. If `xs` is empty: `xs ++ ys = ys`. `h` becomes `∀ x ∈ ys, head! ys ≤ x`, which is exactly the goal.\n\nLet's complete the proof.\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter1\nimport Fad.Chapter12\n\nnamespace Chapter12\nopen Chapter1 (concatMap)\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.1\n   a definição recursiva de `parts` provavelmente teria uma prova mais simples\n   mas não consigo usar na prova por ser `partial`.\n-/\n\nexample : ∀ xs : List Nat, (parts₁ xs).length = 2^(xs.length - 1) := by\n intro xs\n induction xs with\n | nil => simp [parts₁]\n | cons x xs ih =>\n   sorry\n\n/- # Exercício 12.2\n   como parts é partial, não consigo expandir em uma prova. E `parts₁`\n   obviamente não é a primeira definição de `parts` tratada no exercício.\n-/\n\nexample : parts₁ [1,2] = [[[1], [2]], [[1, 2]]] := by\n  unfold parts₁\n  rw [List.foldr]; rw [Function.comp]\n  rw [List.foldr]; rw [Function.comp]\n  simp [concatMap, Chapter1.concat₁]\n  sorry\n  /- simp [List.foldr]\n  simp [cons]\n  simp [cons]\n  simp [glue] -/\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.3 -/\n\ndef parts₃ {α : Type} : List α → List (Partition α) :=\n  let step (x : α) : List (Partition α) → List (Partition α)\n   | [[]] => [[[x]]]\n   | ps => ps.map (cons x) ++ ps.map (glue x)\n  List.foldr step [[]]\n\n-- #eval parts₃ [1,2,3]\n\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.4 -/\n\nsection\nopen List (filter all head!)\n\ndef ok (xs : List Nat) : Bool :=  xs.all (· > 0)\n\ndef okextendl (x : Nat) : Partition Nat → List (Partition Nat) :=\n filter (ok ∘ head!) ∘ exte