      "\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.3 -/\n\ndef parts₃ {α : Type} : List α → List (Partition α) :=\n  let step (x : α) : List (Partition α) → List (Partition α)\n   | [[]] => [[[x]]]\n   | ps => ps.map (cons x) ++ ps.map (glue x)\n  List.foldr step [[]]\n\n-- #eval parts₃ [1,2,3]\n\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.4 -/\n\nsection\nopen List (filter all head!)\n\ndef ok (xs : List Nat) : Bool :=  xs.all (· > 0)\n\ndef okextendl (x : Nat) : Partition Nat → List (Partition Nat) :=\n filter (ok ∘ head!) ∘ extendl x\n\nvariable (h : ∀ x ps, filter (flip all ok) (concatMap (extendl x) ps) =\n              concatMap (okextendl x) (filter (flip all ok) ps))\n\nexample\n  : List.filter (flip List.all ok) ∘ parts₁ = List.foldr (concatMap ∘ okextendl) [[]] := by\n  funext xs\n  unfold parts₁\n  simp [Function.comp]\n  induction xs with\n  | nil =>\n    simp [List.foldr, flip]\n  | cons a as ih =>\n    have h1 := h a\n    sorry\n\nend\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.5 -/\n\nsection\nopen List (range head! tail zipWith and)\n\ndef leftmin  (xs : List Nat) := xs.all (head! xs ≤ ·)\ndef rightmax (xs : List Nat) := xs.all (· ≤ last xs)\ndef ordered  (xs : List Nat) := and $ zipWith (· ≤ ·) xs (tail xs)\ndef nmatch   (xs : List Nat) := and $ zipWith (· ≠ ·) xs (range xs.length)\n\ndef suffixClosed (p : List Nat → Bool) : Prop :=\n    ∀ xs ys, p (xs ++ ys) → p ys\n\ndef prefixClosed (p : List Nat → Bool) : Prop :=\n    ∀ xs ys, p (xs ++ ys) → p xs\n\nexample : suffixClosed leftmin := by\n   unfold suffixClosed\n   intro xs ys\n   unfold leftmin; simp\n   intro h\n   sorry\n```\n\nNow, we need to complete the proof. The goal is to show that if `leftmin (xs ++ ys)` holds, then `leftmin ys` holds. \n\nSo, we need to show that `(∀ x ∈ xs ++ ys, (xs ++ ys).head! ≤ x)` implies `(∀ x ∈ ys, ys.head! ≤ x)`. \n\nTo show this, we can use the fact that `ys` is a suffix of `xs ++ ys`. So, all elements of `ys` are in `xs ++ ys`. Therefore, the property that holds for all elements of `xs ++ ys` should hold for all elements of `ys`. \n\nBut we need to be careful. The head element of `xs ++ ys` could be different from the head element of `ys`. \n\nHowever, note that if `xs` is non-empty, then `(xs ++ ys).head! = xs.head!`. If `xs` is empty, then `(xs ++ ys).head! = ys.head!`. \n\nSo, in the case where `xs` is non-empty, `h` tells us that all elements of `xs ++ ys` are greater than or equal to `xs.head!`. \n\nIn the case where `xs` is empty, `h` tells us that all elements of `xs ++ ys` (which is just `ys`) are greater than or equal to `ys.head!`. \n\nSo, in the case where `xs` is empty, we are done. \n\nIn the case where `xs` is non-empty, we know that all elements of `xs ++ ys` are greater than or equal to `xs.head!`. \n\nTo show that all elements of `ys` are greater than or equal to `ys.head!`. \n\nBut we know that `ys.head!` is in `ys` (if `ys` is non-empty). So, from `h`, we know that `ys.head!` is greater than or equal to `(xs ++ ys).head!`. \n\nIf `xs` is non-empty, then `(xs ++ ys).head! = xs.head!`. So `ys.head! ≥ xs.head!`. \n\nBut we also know from `h` that all elements of `xs ++ ys` are greater than or equal to `xs.head!`. \n\nSo, all elements of `xs` are greater than or equal to `xs.head!` (by `leftmin xs`), and all elements of `ys` are greater than or equal to `xs.head!` (by `h`). \n\nBut we need them to be greater than or equal to `ys.head!`. \n\nHowever, we know that `ys.head!` is an element of `ys`. So, from `h`, we can apply it to `ys.head!`. \n\nWait, `h` is `∀ x ∈ xs ++ ys, (xs ++ ys).head! ≤ x`. \n\nSo, applying this to `x = ys.head!` (which is in `ys`, so in `xs ++ ys`), we get `(xs ++ ys).head! ≤ ys.head!`. \n\nBut we need the converse: `ys.head! ≤ x` for all `x ∈ ys`. \n\nSo, we need to show that `h` implies `∀ x ∈ ys, ys.head! ≤ x`. \n\nTo show this, let `x` be an element of `ys`. Then `x` is also an element of `xs ++ ys`. So, from `h`, we have `(xs ++ ys).head! ≤ x`. \n\nSo, we know that all elements of `xs ++ ys` are greater than or equal to `(xs ++ ys).head!`. \n\nNow, we need to show that all elements of `ys` are greater than or equal to `ys.head!`. \n\nSo, let's write the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter1\nimport Fad.Chapter12\n\nnamespace Chapter12\nopen Chapter1 (concatMap)\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.1\n   a definição recursiva de `parts` provavelmente teria uma prova mais simples\n   mas não consigo usar na prova por ser `partial`.\n-/\n\nexample : ∀ xs : List Nat, (parts₁ xs).length = 2^(xs.length - 1) := by\n intro xs\n induction xs with\n | nil => simp [parts₁]\n | cons x xs ih =>\n   sorry\n\n/- # Exercício 12.2\n   como parts é partial, não consigo expandir em uma prova. E `parts₁`\n   obviamente não é a primeira definição de `parts` tratada no exercício.\n-/\n\nexample : parts₁ [1,2] = [[[1], [2]), [[1, 2]]] := by\n  unfold parts₁\n  rw [List.foldr]; rw [Function.comp]\n  rw [List.foldr]; rw [Function.comp]\n  simp [concatMap, Chapter1.concat₁]\n  sorry\n  /- simp [List.foldr]\n  simp [cons]\n  simp [cons]\n  simp [glue] -/\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.3 -/\n\ndef parts₃ {α : Type} : List α → List (Partition α) :=\n  let step (x : α) : List (Partition α) → List (Partition α)\n   | [[]] => [[[x]]]\n   | ps => ps.map (cons x) ++ ps.map (glue x)\n  List.foldr step [[]]\n\n-- #eval parts₃ [1,2,3]\n\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.4 -/\n\nsection\nopen List (filter all head!)\n\ndef ok (xs : List Nat) : Bool :=  xs.all (· > 0)\n\ndef okextendl (x : Nat) : Partition Nat → List (Partition Nat) :=\n filter (ok ∘ head!) ∘ extendl x\n\nvariable (h : ∀ x ps, filter (flip all ok) (concatMap (extendl x) ps) =\n              concatMap (okextendl x) (filter (flip all ok) ps))\n\nexample\n  : List.filter (flip List.all ok) ∘ parts₁ = List.foldr (concatMap ∘ okextendl) [[]] := by\n  funext xs\n  unfold parts₁\n  simp [Function.comp]\n  induction xs with\n  | nil =>\n    simp [List.foldr, flip]\n  | cons a as ih =>\n    have h1 := h a\n    sorry\n\nend\n\n/- # Exercicio 12.5 -/\n\nsection\nopen List (range head! tail zipWith and)\n\ndef leftmin  (xs